\fs40 \cf2 A note on open source\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 I want to be clear: I'm not anti-open-source. I 
\f3\i am
\f2\i0  open source. My most widely used apps - {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/uncsoft/anubis-oss"}}{\fldrslt Anubis OSS}}, an LLM benchmarking tool for Apple Silicon - is fully open-source, and I contribute to other projects. Open source has given me most of the tools I've built my career on. It has 120 stars on Github.\
But open source is a development model, not a security model. The ability to inspect code is valuable. It is not, by itself, a guarantee that anyone 
\f3\i has
\f2\i0  inspected it, especially in plugin ecosystems accepting contributions from the general public, where a new update can ship at any time and the previous audit (if there was one) is immediately stale. The open-source projects I trust most are the ones that pair source availability with real architectural constraints on what code can do. Visibility without containment is just transparency about your exposure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 Who should care about this\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 If you're writing grocery lists and D&D session notes, honestly, use whatever you want. The threat model doesn't justify the tradeoff.\
But if you're a clinician writing patient observations, Ior drafting a substance use treatment plan that's protected under 42 CFR Part 2 - where 
\f3\i any
\f2\i0  unauthorized disclosure is a federal violation. If you're a lawyer building a case file. If you're a journalist protecting a source. If you're an executive writing strategy documents that would move a stock price. If your writing contains information that could harm real people if it leaks - you should understand the difference between an app that 
\f3\i promises
\f2\i0  not to read your files and an app that 
\f3\i can't
\f2\i0 .\
I wouldn't connect an unvetted third-party system to my clinical data infrastructure. Why would I trust one with my own writing about that same data?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 What CyberWriter actually is\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa640\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 CyberWriter is an AI-integrated scientific and technical writing tool for macOS. It works with standard Markdown files organized in vault-style folders - your notes stay as plain .md files on your filesystem, no proprietary format, no lock-in. Just drop your .md vault in and keep working\
The AI integration supports both API-based models and locally-hosted LLMs - and this is how I actually use it. My strategic plans, clinical deployment analyses, and internal assessments are written in CyberWriter with a local model running on Apple Silicon. The text I write never leaves my machine. There's no cloud round-trip, no third-party processing, no ambiguity about where my data goes. For someone who spends all day thinking about data governance, that matters.\
This is the tool I trust with my own work. I wouldn't ship something I wouldn't use for the things that actually matter to me.\
It's available on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://apps.apple.com/us/app/cyberwriter/id6758079118?mt=12"}}{\fldrslt Apple App Store}} and directly through {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyberwriter.app/"}}{\fldrslt LemonSqueezy}} and it costs less than a month of most cloud-based writing tools.\
I built it because I needed it. I ship it because other people need it too.\
~John
